Spectral Graph Bipartitioning

Many data clustering problems can be interpreted as clustering of vertices of graphs. Graph bipartitioning problem is to partition vertices into subsets such that the connections within subsets are stronger than the connections between different subsets.

Partition of the vertices into two subsetts is done according to signs of the eigenvectors of the second smallest eigenvalue of the Laplacian matrix.

Prerequisites

The reader should be familiar with the basic graph theory, linear algebra and, in particular, eigenvalues and eigenvectors.

Competences

The reader should be able to apply graph spectral bipartitioning and recursive bipartitioning to data clustering problems.

Credits. The notebook was initially derived from M.Sc. Thesis of Ivančica Mirošević.

21.8 μs

Graphs

For more details, see W. H. Haemers, Matrices and Graphs, in L. Hogben, Ed., 'Handbook of Linear Algebra', pp. 39.1-39.14, CRC Press, Boca Raton, 2014. and S. Butler and F. Chung, Spectral Graph Theory, ibid., pp. 47.1-47.6 and the references therein.

Definitions

A weighted graph is an ordered triplet G=(V,E,ω), where V={1,2,3,...,n} is the set of vertices , E={(i,j)} is a set of edges connecting vertices, and ω is a set of weights of edges. We assume G is undirected.

13.3 μs

Adjacency matrix of graph G is the matrix A defined as

Aij={1if (i,j)∈E,0otherwise.

Weight matrix of graph G is the matrix W defined as

Wij={ω(e)if e=(i,j)∈E,0otherwise.

Laplacian matrix of graph G is the matrix

L=D−W,

where D=diag⁡(d1,d2,…,dn) with di=∑k=1nWik for i=1,…,n.

Normalized Laplacian matrix is the matrix

Ln=D−1/2LD−1/2≡D−1/2(D−W)D−1/2

(diagonally scaled L).

Incidence matrix of graph G is the |V|×|E| matrix IG. Each row of IG corresponds to a vertex of G and each column corresponds to an edge of G. In the column corresponding to en edge e=(i,j), all elements are zero except the ones in the i-th and j-th row, which are equal to ω(e) and −ω(e), respectively.

19.1 μs

Facts

  1. L=IGIGT.

  2. L is symmetric PSD matrix.

  3. L1=0 for 1=[1,...,1]T, thus 0 is an eigenvalue of L

and 1 is the corresponding eigenvector.

  1. If G has c connected components, then L has c eigenvalues equal to 0.

  2. For every x∈Rn, it holds

xTLx=∑i<jWij(xi−xj)2

.

  1. For every x∈Rn and α,β∈R, it holds

(αx+β1)TL(αx+β1)=α2xTLx

.

  1. Assume that the eigenvalues of L are increasingly ordered. Then,

0=λ1(L)≤λ2(L)≤⋯≤λn(L)≤2maxi=1,⋯,ndi.

  1. σ(Ln)⊆[0,2].

Bipartitioning

Definitions

Let π={V1,V2} be a partition of V with V1,V2≠∅.

Cut of partition π is the sum of weights of all edges between V1 and V2,

cut⁡(π)≡cut⁡(V1,V2)=∑i∈V1j∈V2Wij.

Weight of vertex i∈V is the sum of the weights of all egdges emanating from i, ω(i)=∑j=1nWij.

Weight of a subset V¯⊂V is the sum of the weights of all vertices in V¯,

ω(V¯)=∑i∈V¯ω(i)

.

Proportional cut of partition π is

pcut⁡(π)=cut⁡(π)|V1|+cut⁡(π)|V2|.

Normalized cut of partition π is

ncut⁡(π)=cut⁡(π)ω(V1)+cut⁡(π)ω(V2).

28.1 μs

Example

Consider the following partitions (all edges have unit weights):

Left partition is π, right partition is π′.

1.8 s

Facts

  1. The informal description of the bipartitioning problem can be formulated as

two problems,

arg minπ⁡pcut⁡(π)orarg minπ⁡ncut⁡(π).

The first problem favors partitions into subsets with similar numbers of vertices, while the second problem favors partitions into subsets with similar weights.

  1. Both problems are NP-hard.

  2. Approximate solutions can be computed by suitable relaxations in O(n2) operations.

  3. The partition π is defined by the vector y such that

yi={12for i∈V1−12for i∈V2

The proportional cut problem can be formulated as the discrete proportional cut problem

minyi∈{−12,12}|yT1|≤β12∑i,j(yi−yj)2Wij.

Parameter β controls the number of vertices in each subset.

  1. The normalized cut problem can be formulated as the discrete normalized cut problem

minyi∈{−12,12}|yTD1|≤β12∑i,j(yi−yj)2Wij.

Parameter β controls the weights of each subset.

  1. Using the Fact 5 above, the discrete proportional cut problem can be

formulated as the relaxed proportional cut problem

miny∈Rn|yT1|≤2βnyTy=1yTLy.

Similarly, the discrete normalized cut problem can be formulated as the relaxed normalized cut problem

miny∈Rn|yTD1|≤βθnyTDy=1yTLny.

  1. The Main Theorem.

Let A∈Rn×n be a symmetric matrix with eigenvalues λ1<λ2<λ3≤⋯≤λn and let v[1],v[2],…,v[n] be the corresponding eigenvectors. For the fixed 0≤α<1, the solution of the problem

miny∈Rn|yTv[1]|≤αyTy=1yTAy

is y=±αv[1]±1−α2v[2].

For the proof see D. J. Higham and M. Kibble, A Unified View of Spectral Clustering, Theorem 3.1, p. 7.

  1. For 0≤β<n2, the solution of the relaxed proportional cut problem is

y=±2βnn1±1−4β2n2v[2],

where v[2] is an eigenvector corresponding to λ2(L). v[2] the Fiedler vector.

Since the first summand carries no information, V is partitioned according to the signs of the components of v[2]:

V1={i:vi[2]<0},V2={i:vi[2]≥0}.

Notice that the value of β is irrelevant for the solution.

  1. For

0≤β<θn∥D121∥2,

the solution of the relaxed normalized cut problem is

y=±βθn∥D121∥221±1−β2θn∥D121∥22D−12vn[2],

where vn[2] is an eigenvector corresponding to λ2(Ln). Vn is partitioned according to the signs of the components of vn[2], as above.

  1. Neither of the relaxed algorithms is guaranteed to solve exactly the true proportional / normalized cut problem. However, the computed solutions are in the right direction.

Whether to use proportional or normalized cut formulation, depends upon the specific problem.

Concentric circles

A complete graph has edges connecting each pair of vertices.

To a set of points X={x1,x2,⋯,xm} , where xi∈Rn, we assign a weighted complete graph G=(V,E) with m vertices, where the vertex j∈V corresponds to the point xj∈X.

The main idea is to assign weight of an edge e=(i,j) which reflects the distance between xi and xj, something like ω(e)=1dist⁡(xi,xj).

However, this has to be implemented with care. For example, using simple Euclidean distance yield the same results as the function kmeans(). In this example we use Gaussian kernel, that is

ω(e)=e−∥xi−xj∥22/σ2,

where the choice of σ is based on experience.

The computation of various distances is implemented in the package Distances.jl.

We will construct the Laplace matrix directly.

Recursive bipartitioning

Definitions

Let G=(V,E) be a weighted graph with weights ω.

Let πk={V1,V2,...,Vk} be a k-partition of V, with Vi≠∅ for i=1,…,k.

The previous definition of cut(π)≡cut(π2) extends naturally to k-partition.

A cut of a partition πk is

cut⁡(πk)=∑i<jcut⁡(Vi,Vj),

where cut⁡(Vi,Vj) is interpreted as a cut of the bipartition of the subgraph of G with vertices V1∪V2.

Proportional cut of a partition πk is

pcut⁡(πk)=∑i,j=1ki<j(cut⁡(Vi,Vj)|Vi|+cut⁡(Vi,Vj)|Vj|)=∑i=1kcut⁡(Vi,V∖Vi)|Vi|.

Normalized cut of a partition πk is

ncut⁡(πk)=∑i,j=1ki<j(cut⁡(Vi,Vj)ω(Vi)+cut⁡(Vi,Vj)ω(Vj))=∑i=1kcut⁡(Vi,V∖Vi)ω(Vi).

Facts

If we want to cluster vertices of graph G=(V,E) into k clusters, we can apply the following recursive algorithm:

  1. Initialization. Compute the bipartition π={V1,V2} of V. Set the counter c=2.

  2. Recursion. While c<k repeat:

    1. Compute the bipartition of each subset of V.

    1. Among all (c+1)-partitions, choose the one with the smallest pcut⁡(πc+1) or

    ncut⁡(πc+1), respectively.

    1. Set c=c+1.

  3. Stop.

There is no guarantee for optimality of this algorithm. Clearly, the optimal k-partiton may be a subpartition of one of the discarded partitions.
